<section xml:id="Angles_and_Their_Measure">
  <title>Angles and Their Measure</title>
  <introduction>
    <p> One method people use to identify their position is by looking at the <em>latitude</em>. <idx>
        <h>latitude</h>
      </idx> These imaginary lines that form circles around the Earth run
      parallel to the Equator. The latitude of a place is defined as the angle between a line drawn
      from the center of the earth to that point and the equatorial plane. For any point in the
      Northern Hemisphere, a navigator can measure their latitude by determining the angle <em>
      Hōkūpaʻa</em> (also known as <em>Kūmau</em>, North Star, or Polaris) makes with the horizon. </p>
    <image xml:id="angles-Hokupaa" width="100%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=6]
        \draw (0,0)--(-0.5,0);
        \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (1.1,0) node[right,xshift=0.1] {Horizon};
        \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (30:1.2);
        \draw[line width=2pt] (0:0.3) arc (0:30:0.3) node[midway, right,xshift=0.05,yshift=2.7]
        {Angle of H\={o}k\={u}pa`a};
        \node [black,scale=1.5] at (30:1.25) {\(\bigstar\)};
        \node [yellow] at (30:1.25) {\(\bigstar\)};
        \node at (1.27,0.63) {Hokupa`a};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      When voyaging,
      knowing correct angles can be the difference between finding and missing your destination.
      Navigators pay close attention to angles on the Hawaiian Star Compass to determine where
      celestial bodies enter and exit the sky as well as where wind and current come from.
      In this section,
      we will examine the properties of angles and their measure.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p> A <term>ray</term>
          <idx>
            <h>ray</h>
          </idx> is a part of a line that begins at a point <m>O</m> and
          extends in one direction. </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-ray" width="85%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[&lt;-] (-5,0) -- (0,0);
            \draw[->, line width=2pt,blue,-stealth](0,0) -- (5,0) node[black,midway,below]{Ray};
            \node[circle,fill=blue,inner sep=2pt,minimum size=2pt,label=below:{\(O\)}] (a) at (0,0)
            {};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p> We can create an <term>angle</term><idx>
            <h>angle</h>
          </idx>, <m>\theta</m>, by rotating rays. 
        First, we begin with two rays lying on top of each other and beginning at <m>O</m>. 
        We let one ray be fixed and will rotate the second ray about the point <m>O</m>. 
        The ray that is fixed is called the <term>initial
          side</term>
          <idx>
            <h>initial side</h>
          </idx> 
        and the ray that is rotated is called the <term>terminal side</term>
          <idx>
            <h>terminal side</h>
          </idx>. 
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-initial-terminal-side" width="50%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
            \draw[->, line width=2pt,blue,-stealth](0,0) -- (5,0) node[black,midway,below]{Initial
            Side};
            \draw[->, line width=2pt,blue,-stealth](0,0) -- (40:5)
            node[black,midway,left,xshift=-0.5cm]{Terminal Side};
            \node[circle,fill=blue,inner sep=2pt,minimum size=2pt,label=below:{\(O\)}] (a) at (0,0)
            {};
            \draw[red] ([shift=(0:0.8cm)]0,0) arc (0:40:0.8cm);
            \node at (1,0.35) {\(\theta\)};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <p> Greek letters are often used to measure angles. The Greek letters commonly used are <m>
        \theta</m>, <m>\phi</m>, <m>\alpha</m>, <m>\beta</m>, and <m>\gamma</m>. </p>
    </remark>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Degree</title>
    <p> The <term>measure</term>
      <idx>
        <h>measure</h>
      </idx> of an angle is the amount of rotation from the initial side to
      the terminal side. One unit of measuring angles is the degree. One <term>degree</term>, <idx>
        <h>degree</h>
      </idx> denoted by <m>1^{\circ}</m>, is <m>\frac{1}{360}</m> of a complete circular
      revolution, so one full revolution is <m>360^{\circ}</m>. </p>
    <p> Since the Hawaiian Star Compass has 32 houses, we see that each house has <m>
      \frac{360^{\circ}}
        {32}=11.25^{\circ}</m>. If we assume due East corresponds to <m>0^{\circ}</m> and the center
      of the House of Hikina points due East, the border between Hikina and Lā Koʻolau will be half
      the angle of the house, <m>\frac{11.25^{\circ}}{2}=5.625^{\circ}</m>. The angles for the
      remaining boundaries on the Hawaiian Star Compass are shown in <xref
        ref="star-compass-with-angles">Figure</xref>. </p>
