    <p> Although we often use decimals to represent the fractional parts of a degree, it was
      traditionally represented in minutes and seconds. One <term>minute</term>
      <idx>
        <h>minute</h>
      </idx> or <em>arc minute</em>, <idx>
        <h>arc minute</h>
      </idx> denoted <m>1'</m>, is defined as <m>\frac{1}{60}(1^{\circ})</m>
      and one <term>second</term>
      <idx>
        <h>second</h>
      </idx> or <em>arc second</em>, <idx>
        <h>arc second</h>
      </idx> denoted <m>1''</m>, is defined as <m>\frac{1}{60}(1')</m>. </p>
    <remark>
      <title>Conversion Between Degree, Minutes,
        and Seconds</title>
      <md>
        <mrow>1^{\circ}\amp =60' \amp 1'\amp =\left(\frac{1}{60}\right)^{\circ} \amp 1''\amp
          =\left(\frac{1}{3600}\right)^{\circ}</mrow>
        <mrow>1^{\circ}\amp =3600'' \amp 1'\amp =60'' \amp 1''\amp =\left(\frac{1}{60}\right)'</mrow>
      </md>
    </remark>
    <example>
      <title>Convert angle from decimal degrees to degrees/minutes/seconds</title>
      <statement>
        <p> In the Star Compass (<xref ref="star-compass-with-angles">Figure</xref>), the angle that
          divides the houses Manu Hoʻolua (northwest) and Noio Hoʻolua (northwest by west) is <m>
          140.625^{\circ}</m>. Represent <m>140.625^{\circ}</m> in degrees, minutes, and seconds. </p>

      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p> First we will convert <m>0.625^{\circ}</m> to minutes using the conversion <m>
          1^{\circ}=60'</m>, <me>
            0.625^{\circ}=0.625^{\circ}\cdot\frac{60'}{1^{\circ}}=37.5'
          </me>
        </p>
        <p> Since <m>1'=60''</m>, we can convert <m>0.5'</m> to seconds: <m>\displaystyle
          0.5'=0.5'\cdot\frac{60''}{1'}=30''</m>. </p>
        <p> So <m>140.625^{\circ}=140^{\circ}37'30''</m>. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
