    <example>
      <title>Convert angle from degrees/minutes/seconds to decimal degrees</title>
      <statement>
        <p> Convert <m>263^{\circ}24'45''</m> to decimal degrees. </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p> We will first convert <m>24'</m> and <m>45''</m> to degrees. <me>
          24'=24\cdot1'=24\cdot\left(\frac{1}{60}\right)^{\circ}=0.4^{\circ}
          </me>
          and <me>
            45''=45\cdot1''=45\cdot\left(\frac{1}{3600}\right)^{\circ}=0.0125^{\circ}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p> So <m>
          263^{\circ}24'45''=263^{\circ}+24'+45''=263^{\circ}+0.4^{\circ}+0.0125=263.4125^{\circ}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p> If an angle is drawn on the <m>xy</m>-plane and the vertex is at the origin and the
          initial side is on the positive <m>x</m>-axis, then that angle is said to be in <term>standard
          position</term>. <idx>
            <h>standard position</h>
          </idx> If the angle is measured in a counterclockwise
          rotation, the angle is said to be a <term>positive angle</term>
          <idx>
            <h>positive angle</h>
          </idx> and if the angle is measured in a clockwise
          rotation, the angle is said to be a <term>negative angle</term>. <idx>
            <h>negative angle</h>
          </idx>
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-positive-negative-angles">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.25]
            \draw[&lt;->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{$x$};
            \draw[&lt;->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{$y$};
            \filldraw[blue] (1cm,0) circle(1pt);
            \filldraw[blue] (60:1.2cm) circle(1pt);
            \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (1,0);
            \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (60:1.2);
            \draw[->, line width=1.25pt] (0:0.7cm) arc (0:60:0.7cm) node[midway,
            right,xshift=0.05cm,yshift=0.2cm] {positive angle};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1.25cm,y=1.25cm]
            \draw[&lt;->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{$x$};
            \draw[&lt;->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{$y$};
            \filldraw[blue] (1cm,0) circle(1pt);
            \filldraw[blue] (-60:1.2cm) circle(1pt);
            \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (1,0);
            \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (-60:1.2);
            \draw[->, line width=1.25pt] (0:0.7cm) arc (0:-60:0.7cm) node[midway,
            right,xshift=0.05cm,yshift=-0.2cm] {negative angle};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p> When an angle is in standard position, the terminal side will either lie in a quadrant
          or it will lie on the <m>x</m>-axis or <m>y</m>-axis. An angle is called a <term>quadrantal
          angle</term>
          <idx>
            <h>quadrantal angle</h>
          </idx> if the terminal side lies on <m>x</m>-axis or <m>
          y</m>-axis. The two axes divide the plane into four <term>quadrants</term>. <idx>
            <h>quadrants</h>
          </idx> In the Cartesian plane, the four quadrants are Quadrant
          I, II, III, and IV. The corresponding quadrants of Star Compass are Ko&#699;olau (NE),
          Ho&#699;olua (NW), Kona (SE), and Malanai (SW). </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-quadrants-star-compass" width="50%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.25]
            \draw[&lt;->] (-2,0)--(2,0) node[right]{$x$};
            \draw[&lt;->] (0,-2)--(0,2) node[above]{$y$};
            \node at (1,1) [ align=center] {I \\ Ko`olau};
            \node at (-1,1) [ align=center]{II \\ Ho`olua};
            \node at (-1,-1) [ align=center] {III \\ Kona};
            \node at (1,-1) [ align=center] {IV \\ Malanai};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <term>Coterminal angles</term>
          <idx>
            <h>coterminal angles</h>
          </idx> are angles in standard position that have the
          same initial side and the same terminal side. Any angle has infinitely many coterminal
          angles because each time we add or subtract <m>360^{\circ}</m> from it, the resulting
          angle has the same terminal side. </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <title>Coterminal angles</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>90^{\circ}</m> and <m>450^{\circ}</m> are coterminal angles since <m>
          450^{\circ}-360^{\circ}=90^{\circ}</m>. </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p> To determine the quadrant in which an angle lies, add or subtract one revolution (<m>
      360^{\circ}</m>) until you obtain a coterminal angle between <m>0^{\circ}</m> and <m>
      360^{\circ}</m>. The quadrant where the terminal side lies is the quadrant of the angle.
      Quadrantal angles do not lie in any quadrant. </p>
    <example>
      <title>Determine the corresponding house and quadrant in the Star Compass</title>
      <statement>
        <p> Determine the quadrant in which each angle lies and name the corresponding House and
          quadrant in the Star Compass (<xref ref="star-compass-with-angles">Figure</xref>). </p>
        <task>
          <p>
            <m>140^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
          <solution>
            <p> Since <m>90^{\circ}\lt 140^{\circ}\lt 180^{\circ}</m>, <m>140^{\circ}</m> lies in
              Quadrant II, or Manu Ho&#699;olua. </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <p>
            <m>-770^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
          <solution>
            <p> Since <m>-770^{\circ}\lt 0^{\circ}</m>, we first add <m>3\times360</m> to <m>
              -770^{\circ}</m> to obtain an angle <m>0^{\circ}</m> and <m>360^{\circ}</m>, <me>
              -770^{\circ}+3\times360^{\circ}=310^{\circ}
              </me> So <m>
              310^{\circ}</m> and <m>-770^{\circ}</m> are coterminal. Since <m>270^{\circ}\lt
              310^{\circ}\lt 360^{\circ}</m>, <m>310^{\circ}</m> lies in Quadrant IV, or Manu
              Malanai. </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <p>
            <m>923^{\circ}</m>
          </p>
          <solution>
            <p> Since <m>923^{\circ}>360^{\circ}</m> we begin by subtracting <m>2\times360^{\circ}</m>
              <me>
              923^{\circ}-2\times360^{\circ}=203^{\circ}
              </me> So <m>
              203^{\circ}</m> and <m>923^{\circ }</m> are coterminal. Since <m>180^{\circ}\lt
              203^{\circ}\lt 270^{\circ}</m>, <m>923^{\circ}</m> lies in Quadrant III or
              &#699;&#256;ina Kona. </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>Determine the corresponding quadrant given its location in the Star Compass</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the corresponding quadrant for Nalani Kona?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Locating Nalani Kona in the Star Compass,
          we see it is in Quadrant III.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p> A <term>central angle</term>
          <idx>
            <h>central angle</h>
          </idx> is a positive angle formed at the center of a
          circle by two radii. </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-central-angle" width="50%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]
            \draw (0,0) circle (1);
            \filldraw[blue] (0,0) circle(1pt);
            \filldraw[blue] (60:1) circle(1pt);
            \filldraw[blue] (120:1) circle(1pt);
            \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (60:1) -- (0,0) node[left,below,yshift=-0.1]{$O$};
            \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (120:1);
            \draw (60:0.3) arc (60:120:0.3);
            \node at (0,0.5) [ align=center] {Central \\ Angle};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Radian</title>
    <p> Another way to measure an angle is with <em>radians</em> which measure the the arc of a
      circle that is formed from an angle. </p>
    <definition xml:id="core-standards-CCSS_MATH_CONTENT_HSF_TF_A_1">
      <title>Definition of a Radian</title>
      <statement>
        <p> The <term>radian measure</term>
          <idx>
            <h>radian measure, of angles</h>
          </idx> of a central angle in a circle is the
          ratio of the length of the arc on a circle subtended by the angle to the radius. If <m>r</m>
          is the radius of the circle, <m>\theta</m> is the angle, and <m>s</m> is the arc length,
          then we have the following <me>
            \theta=\frac{s}{r}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p> A radian is abbreviated by <term>rad</term>. </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-one-rad" width="67%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=2cm,y=2cm]
            \draw[&lt;->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{$x$};
            \draw[&lt;->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{$y$};
            \draw (0,0) circle (1);
            \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0:1) arc (0:45:1) node[midway,above,yshift=0.15,xshift=1.5]
            {$s$};
            \filldraw[blue] (1,0) circle(1pt);
            \filldraw[blue] (45:1) circle(1pt);
            \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (1,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1]{$r$};
            \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (45:1);
            \draw (0:0.3) arc (0:45:0.3) node[midway,right,xshift=0.2,yshift=-0.1]{$\theta$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p> The measure of a central angle obtained when the length of the arc is also equal to the
      radius, <m>r</m>, is called <em>one radian</em> (1 rad). Similarly, if <m>\theta=2</m> rad,
      then the arc length equals <m>2r</m>. </p>
    <image xml:id="fig-radians">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.2]
        \draw[&lt;->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{$x$};
        \draw[&lt;->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{$y$};
        \draw (0,0) circle (1cm);
        \draw[blue] (57.3:0.95cm) -- (57.3:1.05cm);
        \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0:1cm) arc (0:57.3:1cm)
        node[midway,above,yshift=0.15cm,xshift=0.2cm] {$r$};
        \filldraw[blue] (1cm,0) circle(1pt);
        \filldraw[blue] (57.3:1cm) circle(1pt);
        \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (1,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1cm]{$r$};
        \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (57.3:1);
        \draw (0:0.3cm) arc (0:57.3:0.3cm) node[midway,right,xshift=-0.1cm,yshift=0.1cm]{$\theta$=1
        rad};
