    <remark>
      <title>Relationships Between Degrees and Radians</title>
      <p> If a circle with radius 1 is drawn, there are <m>360^{\circ}</m> and the full arc length
        is the circumference, which is <m>2\pi</m> . Therefore, the relationship between degrees and
        radians is: <me>
          360^{\circ}=2\pi \mbox{ radian} , \mbox{or } 180^{\circ}=\pi\mbox{ radian}
        </me>
        <me>
        1\mbox{ radian} =\frac{180^{\circ}}{\pi}
        </me>
        <me>
        1^{\circ}=\frac{\pi}{180}\mbox{ radian}
        </me>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p> To convert degree to radians, multiply by <m>\dfrac{2\pi\mbox{ radians}
        }{360^{\circ}}</m> or <m>\dfrac{\pi\mbox{ radian} }{180^{\circ}}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p> To convert radians to degrees, multiply by <m>\dfrac{360^{\circ}}{2\pi\mbox{
                radians} }</m> or <m>\dfrac{180^{\circ}}{\pi\mbox{ radian} }</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </remark>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Express <m>45^{\circ}</m> in radians. </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle 45^{\circ}=45^{\circ}\left(\frac{2\pi\mbox{ radians}
            }{360^{\circ}}\right)=\frac{\pi}{4}\mbox{radians}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Express <m>\dfrac{5\pi}{6}</m> in degrees. </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \frac{5\pi}{6}\mbox{rad} =\frac{5\pi}{6}\mbox{rad}
            \left(\frac{360^{\circ}}{2\pi\mbox{ rad} }\right)=150^{\circ}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
