  <subsection>
    <title>Arc Length</title>
    <p> Recall the definition of a radian is the ratio of the arc length to the radius of a circle, <m>
      \theta=\frac{s}{r}</m>. Rearranging this, we can obtain a formula for the arc length of a
      circle. </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_arc-length">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>arc length</h>
          </idx> In a circle of radius <m>r</m>, the <em>arc length</em>
          , <m>s</m>, subtended by a central angle (in radians), <m>\theta</m>, is <me>
            s=r\theta </me>
        </p>
        <p> If <m>\theta</m> is given in degrees, then <m>\displaystyle s=2\pi
          r\cdot\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)</m>. </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Find the length of an arc of a circle with radius 10 cm subtended by an angle of <m>
            2</m> radians. </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p> Using the arc formula we get <m>\displaystyle s=10\mbox{cm}
            \cdot 2\mbox{rad}=20\mbox{cm}</m>. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Kiritimati, also known as Christmas Island, is an atoll in the Republic of Kiribati.
          Kiritimati's location west of the International Date Line makes it one of the first places
          in the world to welcome the New Year, while Hawaiʻi is one of the last places. Although
          Kiritimati and Molokaʻi share the same longitude at <m>157^{\circ}12'</m> west (meaning
          Molokaʻi is directly north of Kiritimati), both islands are 24 hours apart. For example,
          if the time on Oʻahu is 3:00 pm on Thursday, then at that same moment it is 3:00 pm on
          Friday in Kiritimati. Find the distance between Kiritimati ( <m>1^{\circ}45'</m> north
          latitude) and Molokaʻi (<m>21^{\circ}08'</m> north latitude). Assume the radius of Earth
          is 3,960 miles and that the central angle between the two islands is the difference in
          their laititudes. </p>
        <image width="75%" source="fig-globe-kiritimati.svg" />
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p> The measure of the central angle between the two islands is <md>
            <mrow>\theta\amp = 21^{\circ}08'-1^{\circ}45'</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = 19^{\circ}23'</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = 19^{\circ}+\frac{23}{60}^{\circ}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp \approx 19.3833^{\circ}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p> To find the distance, we use <xref ref="thm_arc-length">Theorem</xref> to find the arc
          length: <me>
            s=2\pi r\cdot\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)\approx2\pi\cdot(3,960\mbox{ miles}
          )\frac{19.3833^{\circ}}{360^{\circ}}\approx1,340\mbox{ miles}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          So the distance between Kiritimati and Molokaʻi is approximately 1,340 miles.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
