  <subsection xml:id="core-standards-CCSS_MATH_CONTENT_HSG_C_B_5-c">
    <title>Area of a Sector of a Circle</title>
    <definition>
      <title>Area of a Sector</title>
      <p>
        <idx>
          <h>area</h>
          <h>of a sector</h>
        </idx> The <term>area of the sector</term> of a circle of radius <m>
        r</m> formed by a central angle of <m>\theta</m> is <md>
          <mrow>A\amp =\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\cdot\pi\cdot r^2,\mbox{ when \(\theta\) is in
        degrees}</mrow>
          <mrow>A\amp =\frac{1}{2}r^2\theta,\mbox{ when \(\theta\) is in radians}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </definition>
    <p> Notice the ratio <m>\displaystyle\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}</m> is the proportion of the
      angle <m>\theta</m> (in degrees) to one complete circle. Additionally, the circumference of a
      circle is given by <m>2\pi r</m>. Therefore, the arc length is simply the proportion of the
      central angle to the whole circle multiplied by the circumference of the circle. <me>
      s=\mbox{arc length} =\mbox{(proportion of circle)} \cdot\mbox{(circumference)}
      =\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)\cdot(2\pi r)
      </me>
    </p>
    <p> Similarly, the area of a circle is given by <m>\pi r^2</m>. So the area of sector is the
      proportion of the central angle to the whole circle multiplied by the area of the circle. <me>
      A=\mbox{area of sector} =\mbox{(proportion of circle)} \cdot\mbox{(area of circle)}
      =\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)\cdot\left(\pi r^2\right)
      </me>
    </p>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p> Given a circle of radius <m>r</m> formed by a central angle of <m>\theta</m>, then the
          arc length and area of the sector formed by <m>\theta</m> can be expressed as the
          proportion of the angle to the full circle multiplied by the circumference and area of the
          circle, respectively. <me>
            s=\mbox{(proportion of circle)} \cdot\mbox{(circumference)}
          =\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)\cdot(2\pi r)
          </me>
          and <me>
            A=\mbox{(proportion of circle)} \cdot\mbox{(area of circle)}
          =\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)\cdot\left(\pi r^2\right)
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <example xml:id="example-sail-into-wind">
      <statement>
        <p> When sailing, Hōkūleʻa cannot make headway by sailing directly into the wind. It can
          only sail beyond <m>67^{\circ}</m> in either direction from the wind (<xref
            ref="fig_sailing-upwind">Figure</xref>). If Hōkūleʻa sails for 50 miles, what is the
          area of the sector that cannot be sailed? Round your answer to the nearest square mile. </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig_sailing-upwind">
          <caption> Hōkūleʻa cannot sail within <m>67^{\circ}</m> into the direction of the wind. </caption>
          <image xml:id="sailing-upwind" width="75%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[x=3.25cm,y=3.25cm]
              \draw (0,0) circle (1);
              \draw[->] (0,0) -- (157:1.2);
              \draw[->] (0,0) -- (23:1.2);
              \fill[blue,fill opacity=0.1] (157:1) -- (0,0) -- (23:1) arc (23:157:1);
              \filldraw[blue] (0,0) circle(1pt);
              \draw[&lt;->] (23:0.3) arc (23:90:0.3)
              node[midway,above,xshift=0.3,yshift=-0.]{$67^{\circ}$};
              \draw[&lt;->] (90:0.3) arc (90:157:0.3)
              node[midway,above,xshift=-0.3,yshift=-0.]{$67^{\circ}$};
              \draw[&lt;->] (-1.2,0) -- (1.2,0);
              \draw[&lt;-] (0,-1.15) -- (0,1);
              \draw[->] (0,0) -- (-45:1.2);
              \draw[->] (0,0) -- (225:1.2);
              \draw[line width=2pt,->] (0,0.9) -- (0,0.5);
              \draw[line width=2pt,->] (0.2,0.9) -- (0.2,0.5);
              \draw[line width=2pt,->] (-0.2,0.9) -- (-0.2,0.5);
              \node at (0,-1.2) {Downwind};
              \node at (0,1.2) {Upwind};
              \draw ([shift=(23:0.6)]0,0) pic {waa1-top={waacolor}{-67}{0.03}};
              \draw ([shift=(157:0.6)]0,0) pic {waa1-top={waacolor}{67}{0.03}};
              \draw ([shift=(0:0.6)]0,0) pic {waa1-top={waacolor}{-90}{0.03}};
              \draw ([shift=(180:0.6)]0,0) pic {waa1-top={waacolor}{90}{0.03}};
              \draw ([shift=(-45:0.6)]0,0) pic {waa1-top={waacolor}{-135}{0.03}};
              \draw ([shift=(225:0.6)]0,0) pic {waa1-top={waacolor}{135}{0.03}};
              \draw ([shift=(-90:0.6)]0,0) pic {waa1-top={waacolor}{180}{0.03}};
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p> The angle is <m>\theta=2\cdot67^{\circ}=134^{\circ}</m> and the radius is <m>r=50</m>
          miles. So the area is given by <me>
            A=\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\pi\cdot r^2=\frac{134}{360}\pi\cdot 50^2\approx2,923\mbox{
          square miles}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sec_angular_velocity_and_linear_speed">
    <title>Angular Velocity and Linear Speed</title>
    <p> Consider an object moving along a circle as shown below. There are two ways to describe the
      circular motion of this object: <em>linear speed</em> which measures the distance traveled;
      and <em>angular speed</em> which measures the rate at which the central angle changes. </p>
    <image xml:id="fig-angular-velocity-linear-speed" width="33%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.25]
        \draw (0,0) circle (1cm);
        \draw[blue] (45:0.95cm) -- (45:1.05cm);
        \draw[blue] (0:1cm) arc (0:45:1cm) node[midway,above,yshift=0.15cm,xshift=0.2cm] {$s$};
        \filldraw[blue] (1cm,0) circle(1pt);
        \filldraw[blue] (45:1cm) circle(1pt);
        \filldraw[blue] (0,0) circle(1pt);
        \draw[blue] (0,0) -- (1,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1cm]{r};
        \draw[blue] (0,0) -- (45:1);
        \draw (0:0.3cm) arc (0:45:0.3cm) node[midway,above,xshift=0.2cm,yshift=-0.1cm]{$\theta$};
        \draw[->] (0:0.8cm) arc (0:45:0.8cm);
        \end{tikzpicture}
</latex-image>
    </image>
    <definition>
      <title>Linear Speed</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>Speed</h>
            <h>Linear</h>
          </idx>
          <idx>
            <h>linear speed</h>
          </idx> Suppose an object moves along a circle with radius <m>
          r</m> and <m>\theta</m> (measured in radians) is the angle transversed in time <m>t</m>.
          Let <m>s</m> be the distance the object traveled in time <m>t</m>. Then the <term>linear
          speed</term>, <m>v</m>, of the object is given by <me>
            v=\frac{s}{t}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition>
      <title>Angular Speed</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>Speed</h>
            <h>Angular</h>
          </idx>
          <idx>
            <h>angular speed</h>
          </idx> Suppose an object moves along a circle. Let <m>
          \theta</m> (measured in radians) be the angle transversed by the object in time <m>t</m>.
          The <term>angular speed</term>, <m>\omega</m>, of the object is given by <me>
          \omega=\frac{\theta}{t}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p> Notice that we can rearrange the angular speed to get <m>\theta=\omega t</m>. Since <m>s</m>
      is an arc length, we have <m>s=r\theta</m>, and thus we can write the linear speed as <me>
      v=\frac{s}{t}=\frac{r\theta}{t}=\frac{r\omega t}{t}=r\omega
      </me>
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def_linear-speed">
      <title>Linear Speed</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>Speed</h>
            <h>Linear</h>
          </idx>
          <idx>
            <h>linear speed</h>
          </idx> Suppose an object moves along a circle with radius <m>
          r</m> and an angular speed <m>\omega</m> (measured in radians per unit time). Then the <term>linear
          speed</term>, <m>v</m>, of the object is given by <me>
            v=r\omega
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="une-example">
      <title>Une</title>
      <statement>
        <image xml:id="une-fig">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw pic {waa-single-side={waacolor}{0}{1}};
            \draw [color=waacolor] (-3.876609754200976,0.19897036596795284) --
            (-4.431283335105596,0.2303260794507818) -- (-4.898394752926766,0.1524741764805878) --
            (-5.040559097481035,-0.0946209938161149) -- (-4.826183093167583,-0.28733251913671576) --
            (-4.373740624214583,-0.17924262747936925) -- (-3.85247136084893,0.09154660024304466) --
            (-0.73043162509275,0.7961615849190451) -- (-0.7741285435525864,0.9054038810686352) --
            cycle;
            \fill[color=brown,fill=brown,fill opacity=0.4] (-3.876609754200976,0.19897036596795284)
            -- (-4.431283335105596,0.2303260794507818) -- (-4.898394752926766,0.1524741764805878) --
            (-5.040559097481035,-0.0946209938161149) -- (-4.826183093167583,-0.28733251913671576) --
            (-4.373740624214583,-0.17924262747936925) -- (-3.85247136084893,0.09154660024304466) --
            (-0.73043162509275,0.7961615849190451) -- (-0.7741285435525864,0.9054038810686352) --
            cycle;
            \draw[->] ([shift=(131.4:1.13)]0.15,-0.3) arc (-60:120:0.3cm);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p> One method a waʻa uses to change direction is with the <em>hoe uli</em>, or the steering paddle. When a sharp turn is
          needed for maneuvers such as tacking, the steersperson will turn the handle of the hoe uli
          in a circular motion, as a lever to scoop the paddle in the water and change the heading
          of a vessel. This move called <em>une</em> (prounced oo-NAY although it is often
          mispronounced as oo-NEE) <!--
          https://www.lokahicanoeclub.org/culture/canoeterms.php --> literally translates to <q>lever.</q> If the steerperson is
          performing an une at a rate of 25 rotations per minute and the radius of the circular
          movement is 2 feet, calculate <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                the angular speed measured in radians per minute
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                the linear speed of the hoe uli in miles per hour (round your answer to two decimal
          places)
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <video youtube="1A2UDMDE3Uc" />
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p> We are given the angular speed is <m>\omega=25</m> revolutions per minute. To
                convert our angular speed to radians per minute, we use the fact that one revolution
                is <m>2\pi</m> radians to get <me>
                  \omega=25\frac{\mbox{revolution} }{\mbox{minute} }=25\frac{\mbox{rev}
                }{\mbox{minute} }\cdot2\pi\frac{\mbox{radians} }{\mbox{revolution}
                }=50\pi\frac{\mbox{radians} }{\mbox{minute} }
                </me>
                Thus the hoe uli is moving at an angular speed of <m>50\pi</m> radians per second. </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p> Since the radius is <m>r=2</m> ft and the angular speed is <m>\omega=180</m> is
                measure in radians per minute we can <xref ref="def_linear-speed">Definition</xref>
                to calculate the linear speed <me>
                  v=r\omega=2\mbox{ft} \cdot50\pi\frac{\mbox{rad} }{\mbox{min}
                }\cdot\frac{\mbox{mile} }{5280\mbox{ft} }\cdot\frac{60\mbox{min} }{\mbox{hr}
                }\approx3.57\frac{\mbox{miles} }{\mbox{hour} }
                </me>
                Thus the steersperson is moving the hoe uli at a linear speed of 3.57 mph. </p>
              <!-- <video youtube="uzD2k-CqbDE?t=504" /> -->
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
